00928","H00929","H00930","H00931","H00932","H00933","H00934","H00935"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Jahleel Woodbridge","first_name":"Jahleel","last_name":"Woodbridge","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST023"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"politics","header":"Kidnapped from home at midnight by Shays men","body":"When Shays' Rebellion reached Stockbridge in 1787, the insurrectionists targeted Judge Woodbridge — symbol of the 'silk stocking aristocracy.' They broke into his home at midnight, pillaged it, and carried him off as a prisoner to Great Barrington; he negotiated his own release and met the rescue party halfway home. Edward Bellamy's 1879 novel 'The Duke of Stockbridge' drew on these events."},{"number":2,"category":"education","header":"Learned the Mahican language at Mission School","body":"Growing up in Stockbridge from age one, he attended the Indian Mission School and was tutored by his uncle Timothy Woodbridge and Jonathan Edwards — learning the Mahican language in the process. Princeton followed in 1761, and Berkshire County militia service by 1764."},{"number":3,"category":"politics","header":"Paid Stockbridge Indian soldiers to prevent strong drink","body":"On 5 July 1775 the Third Provincial Congress of Massachusetts resolved that wages of Stockbridge Indians serving in the war be paid directly to Woodbridge and Timothy Edwards. The Indians had requested the arrangement themselves — 'being sensible of their want of prudence in disposing of their money, [they were] desirous that this Congress, in their wisdom, would devise some method to prevent their getting too much strong drink.'"}],"slug":"jahleel-woodbridge-1738"},"H00380":{"id":"H00380","has_descendants_do